, whether it has any counters on it or Auras attached to it, or any non-copy effects that have changed its power, toughness, types, color, and so on.£5/29/2014: If the copied creature has {X} in its mana cost (such as Grenzo, Dungeon Warden), X is considered to be 0.£5/29/2014: If the chosen creature is copying something else (for example, if the chosen creature is another Dack’s Duplicate), then Dack’s Duplicate enters the battlefield as whatever the chosen creature is copying. It will have haste and dethrone.£5/29/2014: If the chosen creature is a token, Dack’s Duplicate copies the original characteristics of that token as stated by the effect that put the token onto the battlefield. Dack’s Duplicate is not a token, even when copying one.£5/29/2014: Any enters-the-battlefield abilities of the copied creature will trigger when Dack’s Duplicate enters the battlefield. Any “as [this creature] enters the battlefield” or “[this creature] enters the battlefield with” abilities of the chosen creature will also work.£5/29/2014: If Dack’s Duplicate somehow enters the battlefield at the same time as another creature, Dack’s Duplicate can’t become a copy of that creature. You may choose only a creature that’s already on the battlefield.£5/29/2014: You can choose to not copy anything. In that case, Dack’s Duplicate enters the battlefield as a 0/0 Shapeshifter creature, and will probably die almost immediately, when state-based actions are next performed.£5/29/2014: Dethrone doesn’t trigger if the creature attacks a planeswalker, even if its controller has the most life.£5/29/2014: Once dethrone triggers, it doesn’t matter what happens to the players’ life totals before the ability resolves. You’ll put a +1/+1 counter on the creature even if the defending player doesn’t have the most life as the ability resolves.£5/29/2014: The +1/+1 counter is put on the creature before blockers are declared.£5/29/2014: In a Two-Headed Giant game, dethrone will trigger if the creature attacks